WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.650 --> 00:00:13.980
[jazz music playing]

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:20.080
&gt;&gt;Gopi: Dave Barry has a staggering ambition.
He wants to become the President of the United

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.080
States of America.

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:22.080
[audience chuckles]

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:29.609
And his highest priority will be to issue
the death penalty to the person responsible

00:00:29.609 --> 00:00:33.000
for making Americans install low-flow toilets.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.739
[audience laughs and claps]

00:00:36.739 --> 00:00:46.119
Good afternoon, Googlers. My name is Gopi
Kallayil. I work in Google marketing and we

00:00:46.119 --> 00:00:53.290
all knew this day would finally come and our
young company is prepared for it. We knew

00:00:53.290 --> 00:01:00.750
that one day Dave Barry would visit the Googleplex
and inspect our toilets.

00:01:00.750 --> 00:01:01.750
[hehe]

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:03.010
[audience chuckles]

00:01:03.010 --> 00:01:04.010
[pause]

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:10.720
Dave, I'm happy to tell you that wherever
you go in the Googleplex, you will find the

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:19.080
total, high-tech, high-flow toilet. And Dave,
I know you're hiding backstage, I am not making

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:20.080
this up.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:21.080
[audience laughs]

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:28.900
"So who is the real Dave Barry", I asked Google
last night. And since Google knows everything,

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:34.810
it told me that he was elected Class Clown
of his Pleasantville High School class in

00:01:34.810 --> 00:01:37.159
1965.

00:01:37.159 --> 00:01:39.520
[pause]

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:45.470
For 25 years he wrote a syndicated column
that was published in over 500 newspapers,

00:01:45.470 --> 00:01:55.510
and in 1988 he won the Pulitzer Prize for
Commentary. It left his critics speechless.

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:57.600
[pause]

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:03.450
And he's written over 30 books as well along
the way. Now, you would think that when you've

00:02:03.450 --> 00:02:12.170
done so much, a man would grow up, and maybe
get a membership card with the AARP, or something.

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:17.340
No, but not Dave. He's gone on to write his
next book and he's here today to tell us about

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:24.999
it. Dave Barry's, "I'll Mature When I'm Dead:
Dave Barry's Amazing Tales of Adulthood."

00:02:24.999 --> 00:02:31.810
I'm delighted to welcome to the Google campus
one of the finest, funniest writers in the

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:38.049
entire world; a man who hopes to become, one
day, the President of the United States of

00:02:38.049 --> 00:02:48.810
America. Ladies and gentlemen, here to talk
about his latest book, is Mr. Dave Barry.

00:02:48.810 --> 00:02:50.730
[clapping]

00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:56.489
&gt;&gt;Dave: Thank you.

00:02:56.489 --> 00:02:58.419
[clapping]

00:02:58.419 --> 00:03:03.090
Gobi's available for weddings, Bar mitzvahs,
and I thank you for the introduction. I just

00:03:03.090 --> 00:03:05.240
want to clarify the toilet thing. I don't
think about them all the time.--

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:06.969
[man laughs]

00:03:06.969 --> 00:03:13.749
I did write a, a number of columns back when
Congress decided to switch to low-flow toilets

00:03:13.749 --> 00:03:18.620
and I didn't realize that, until I-I-I moved
to a house that had them that...and, I, I-I

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:23.790
was u-up-upset cause i-it, it, I mean, now
we're used to it but young people don't realize

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:26.239
that there was a time this country had great
toilets.

00:03:26.239 --> 00:03:27.239
[laughter]

00:03:27.239 --> 00:03:31.370
We had the best toilets in the world. We had
toilets that could suck down a mature sheep.

00:03:31.370 --> 00:03:32.370
[laughter]

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:37.040
But, now we, we have, anyway. I'm not gonna
get too far into the toilets. I think Gobi

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:42.309
covered that pretty well. This is actually
not my first visit to the Googleplex. This

00:03:42.309 --> 00:03:47.139
is my second. The people applauding don't
know why, hehehe, maybe you were there.

00:03:47.139 --> 00:03:52.420
I'm in a band of authors called The Rock Bottom
Remainders. And it was Amy Tan, one of our

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:57.199
founding members, who arranged for us to come
here and perform. And for those who were here

00:03:57.199 --> 00:03:58.199
that night, I'm sorry--

00:03:58.199 --> 00:03:59.199
[laughter]

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:03.079
But, the idea, the idea, of, of...the band
has been around since 1992 and the original

00:04:03.079 --> 00:04:09.409
idea was, it was going to be a one night thing,
and the idea was to get a bunch of authors

00:04:09.409 --> 00:04:13.339
with musical talent together and play a show
to raise money.

00:04:13.339 --> 00:04:18.940
It was during a bookseller's convention for
a First Amendment cause and the only flaw

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:24.090
in that plan was that it-it turns out none
of the authors had any lit-uhh, musical talent.

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:28.050
But we enjoyed playing so much that we, we
just kept together and we still play. And

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:30.930
as Amy once put it, "I would do this to kill
the whales."

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.410
[laughter]

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:38.759
Although, to my knowledge no whale has ever
been killed as a result of any, our Remainders

00:04:38.759 --> 00:04:41.430
performance. But we, we, our genre we call
it "Hard Listening Music".

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:42.430
[laughter]

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:48.770
And those of you who were here that night
may remember our, we-the, I call our, the

00:04:48.770 --> 00:04:54.660
technique we, we play "The Rumor Method" of
music. Which is to say, everybody is holding

00:04:54.660 --> 00:05:00.840
an instrument or, of some kind and everybody's
playing something. And then a rumor goes around

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:02.060
that there might have been a might have been
a chord change.

00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:03.060
[laughter]

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:07.590
Whoa. Anyway, I'll switch to something else
although not the, the same, necessarily the

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:13.340
same something else. Anyway, so, I went, I
have been here, had a-a nice tour, it was

00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:19.520
impressed as I'm sure everybody is by this
fascinating, huge, complex, mysterious operation.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:24.840
And I'm, of course, a Googler. I-I'm a l-long-time
user of Google. In fact, I, it has really

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:30.120
changed my work habits as it, I suppose most
people. When I need to know something I used

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:35.090
to have to look it up, you know, with an almanac
or something and now I just get on Google

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:40.639
and like, two hours later I'm looking at something
completely unrelated. And I uhh--

00:05:40.639 --> 00:05:41.639
[laughter]

00:05:41.639 --> 00:05:46.900
As I, I'm, thanks to you guys; I'm wasting
time faster than ever before. And, and I do

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:50.449
appre.. no, I use Google all the time. What
I need, and I-I've said that I-I need a search

00:05:50.449 --> 00:05:56.180
engine, I need a, a Goog, a special Google
that whatever I type in for a search it returns,

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:57.180
"Get back to work."

00:05:57.180 --> 00:05:58.180
[laughter]

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:02.860
So if you could work on that. I'm gonna talk
a little bit about my and I was hoping to

00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:07.360
do actually a dramatic reading from it using
somebody in the audience as a foil. But I'll

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.500
get to that in a little.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:14.840
This is a book of essays. All but one of which
have never appeared anywhere else. Most, most

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.520
of my, a lot of books I, I've written over
the years really just compilations of, of

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:23.310
newspaper columns. This is not; these are
original essays written for this book but

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:27.259
the one that the, one exception, the one that
sort of started the idea of, of, in my mind,

00:06:27.259 --> 00:06:33.500
of writing this book and it's really kind
of the same, kind of the same inspiration

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:38.231
that inspired William Faulkner and Marcel
Proust and, a colonoscopy.

00:06:38.231 --> 00:06:39.370
[laughter]

00:06:39.370 --> 00:06:43.740
Now most of you fortunately for yourselves
are too young to have had this experience

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:47.810
but eventually in life you'll, you'll, you'll
be advised that you need to get a colonoscopy.

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:53.810
I went way, way past the time when you're
supposed to get one. And I and I didn't get

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:54.990
it.

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:59.430
And then I got a call, actually got an email
from my brother, Sam, who lives in San Francisco,

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:05.759
saying that he had just, he's younger than
I am but much more responsible. And his, his

00:07:05.759 --> 00:07:10.139
email said that he had gotten a colonoscopy
and they had found that he had cancer. And

00:07:10.139 --> 00:07:14.270
they caught it really early and just to clear
that up, he's fine now. They, they treated

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:19.340
it and he's, he's fine. But it was a little,
it was quite scary. And the email said, "The

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:25.129
doctors told me that I should contact my siblings
and make sure that they've been screened also."

00:07:25.129 --> 00:07:29.150
And he said to me, "I'm sure you've been screened
already", because I'm older than he is.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:34.610
And of course I hadn't. And the reason I hadn't,
and it's the big fear most people have, it's,

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:38.240
it's the, the, the im-, the impression people
have about a colonoscopy is that it is going

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:42.659
to be awful because they're gonna stick a
tube 17,000 feet up your butt.

00:07:42.659 --> 00:07:43.789
[laughter]

00:07:43.789 --> 00:07:49.750
And they are. That's exactly what they do.
In fact, the big danger of the procedure is

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:51.919
that the tube will go out of you and enter
another patient.

00:07:51.919 --> 00:07:52.919
[laughter]

00:07:52.919 --> 00:07:59.419
They have a guy with an ax to cut it off in
case it gets loose in the room. But, it's

00:07:59.419 --> 00:08:04.279
nothing because it's a lot like the '60s.
They give you drugs--

00:08:04.279 --> 00:08:05.279
[laughter]

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:09.699
and you don't remember it. You don't remember
any of it. I, when I, was, was done, I asked,

00:08:09.699 --> 00:08:12.560
I sin-sincerely didn't know it was done and
it, I felt so good I thought, "Well let's

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:13.789
do it again while we're"--

00:08:13.789 --> 00:08:14.789
[laughter]

00:08:14.789 --> 00:08:19.509
That wasn't so bad. The only bad part of the
actual procedure, something to, something

00:08:19.509 --> 00:08:25.159
to keep in mind, the procedure room they had,
and this is fairly common I gather in rooms

00:08:25.159 --> 00:08:28.029
where this kinds of procedures going on, they
had music playing.

00:08:28.029 --> 00:08:32.760
I think that's supposed to relax you and it
would have except for that when they were

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:38.630
just putting me under with the stuff and Dr.
Sable was coming toward me with the tube,

00:08:38.630 --> 00:08:41.669
the song that came on the PA was "Dancing
Queen"--

00:08:41.669 --> 00:08:42.669
[laughter]

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:48.190
by ABBA. So you, that's really the last song
you want to hear when a guy is coming at you

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:51.270
with a tube and you're about to be unconscious.
So anyway--

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:52.270
[laughter]

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:56.670
ask for the non-ABBA version. The other part,
and I don't want to get too graphic here,

00:08:56.670 --> 00:09:02.000
those of you who have been through this experience
will know what I'm talking about. The preparation

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.940
for the colonoscopy is a little bit intense
because they have to clean you out pretty

00:09:05.940 --> 00:09:09.250
good. So they give you nuclear laxative.

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:10.530
[laughter]

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:13.260
So powerful that you're bowels travel into
the future.

00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:14.600
[laughter]

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:16.450
And you expel food that you have not even
eaten yet.

00:09:16.450 --> 00:09:17.450
[laughter]

00:09:17.450 --> 00:09:21.951
Ok. Never, if you've ever seen a space shuttle
launch, that's generally the--

00:09:21.951 --> 00:09:24.320
[laughter]

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:25.320
experience. So anyway--

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:26.320
[laughter]

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:31.600
enough about that. So anyway, that, that,
so I wrote, I wrote an essay about that. That,

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:34.830
mm-at the time I didn't think about writing
a book of essays, so I wrote a book and it

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:38.260
ran in Miami Herald and a bunch of other newspapers
and it, and it, and it, became pretty viral

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:44.060
on the Internet. I got a tre- , a lot, lot
of responses to that, and to this day in fact,

00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:47.850
if, when I get on an airplane people like,
some guy ten rows away will go, "Dave, I got

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:51.860
a colonoscopy!" And, which is not the best
thing to have and--

00:09:51.860 --> 00:09:52.860
[laughter]

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:55.280
people yelling to you and, with all those
other people wondering, "Why is he telling

00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:56.280
him that?"

00:09:56.280 --> 00:09:58.010
[audience chuckles]

00:09:58.010 --> 00:10:03.310
So anyway, I thought that, I kind of enjoyed
that, I hadn't been writing a column for awhile,

00:10:03.310 --> 00:10:07.071
I've been doing other things. But I kind of
enjoyed writing that essay and I enjoyed the

00:10:07.071 --> 00:10:10.640
fact that I could write a longer essay and,
and, when I was writing newspaper columns

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.920
they, they had to be about 650 words. Ki-kinda
had to keep them short and so I, I came up

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:19.680
with the idea, of, of writing a series of
essays and, and turn them into a book and

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:24.270
that's, that's really what this became; how
this book came to be.

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:30.160
One of the topics I talk about extensively
in the book is, is my city. I live in Miami.

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:34.110
I moved there in 1986 from the United States.

00:10:34.110 --> 00:10:35.110
[laughter]

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:41.000
And I always feel like, a, sort of an ambassador
for the City of Miami because it has a very

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.840
poor image. Every year the Zogby organization
does a poll where they ask people what their

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:51.340
impressions are of major metropolitan areas.
Every year Miami does poorly in this poll.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:58.400
The last one I saw, 67 percent of the respondents
said that they thought of Miami as a dangerous,

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:05.180
violent place. And that's really disturbing
to me. I, I want to track those people down

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:06.180
and kill them.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:07.480
[laughter]

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:10.310
Because it's not, I mean, it's like any other
place. There's, there's, there's good and

00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:14.820
there's bad, but really is a, a wonderful
city. So I wrote a chapter in, in the book

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:19.480
which is a, an essay in the book which is
essentially a visitor's guide to Miami, which

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:25.820
starts out with my, my proposed solution to
the, the tourism image problem which is a-a

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:31.370
new tourism promotion campaign based on the
slogan, "Come back to Miami. We weren't shooting

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:32.370
at you."

00:11:32.370 --> 00:11:33.370
[laughter]

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:34.370
And

00:11:34.370 --> 00:11:35.370
[clears throat]

00:11:35.370 --> 00:11:39.160
I talk in there about what, what's, things
to do, things not to do, where to go, where

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:43.370
not to go. My, my main place not to go in
Miami is outdoors.

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:44.370
[laughter]

00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:51.140
That can be pretty dangerous. And, and, also
driving, can, is a little hazardous in Miami.

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:55.560
When I first got there I thought, "These people
don't know the law." I now realize that everybody

00:11:55.560 --> 00:11:59.720
in Miami is driving according to the law of
his or her individual country of origin.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:01.660
[laughter]

00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:05.100
And apparently there's countries where it's
traditional to put on that left turn signal

00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:06.100
first thing in the morning.

00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:07.100
[laughter]

