00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:26.319
&gt;&gt;Woman #1: Hi, I was just wondering if you
could speak a little bit about how you got

00:45:26.319 --> 00:45:27.319
your start in comedy writing.

00:45:27.319 --> 00:45:28.319
&gt;&gt;Dave: Yeah.

00:45:28.319 --> 00:45:29.319
&gt;&gt;Woman #1: And maybe what's helped you to
be so successful.

00:45:29.319 --> 00:45:32.250
&gt;&gt;Dave: I, I went, I went, when I got out
of college as an English major, so I, when

00:45:32.250 --> 00:45:36.940
I got out of college, I went to Haverford
College in Pennsylvania and I got out with

00:45:36.940 --> 00:45:41.589
no useful skills whatsoever. I mean, unless
you counted being able to name metaphysical

00:45:41.589 --> 00:45:45.700
poets or something. But you never saw an ad
that said, "We're looking for people who can

00:45:45.700 --> 00:45:52.440
name metaphysical poets." And there were,
so I, I, went to work for a newspaper called

00:45:52.440 --> 00:45:56.579
the Daily Local News in Westchester, Pennsylvania,
and that was actually the name, "Daily Local

00:45:56.579 --> 00:45:59.700
News", sounds like the newspaper SuperBoy
delivered.

00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:05.219
And it was, it was one of those, it was a
very small-town paper, like small-time news.

00:46:05.219 --> 00:46:09.800
Like if somebody were to grow a, a zucchini
that looked, that had, looked like Dwight

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:13.790
Eisenhower or something we'd take a picture
of it and put it on the front page. That was

00:46:13.790 --> 00:46:18.579
big news at the Daily Local. We actually,
we had a front page, it's not the best edited

00:46:18.579 --> 00:46:24.030
newspaper in the world, we had a front page
story with the headline once, "Women Beats

00:46:24.030 --> 00:46:25.049
Off Would-be Rapist."

00:46:25.049 --> 00:46:27.829
[audience laughs]

00:46:27.829 --> 00:46:34.979
So anyway, but it was really good training
for me. I, I, I covered everything. I wrote

00:46:34.979 --> 00:46:40.279
obituaries, I went to school board meetings,
and I went to all these, and, but, while I,

00:46:40.279 --> 00:46:44.420
while I did that, once a week I would write
a column, a little column because it was a

00:46:44.420 --> 00:46:47.489
little paper. You could write and do whatever
you want. And I had written some col-, some

00:46:47.489 --> 00:46:51.839
humor columns in high school and college but
this was actually in a real newspaper and

00:46:51.839 --> 00:46:55.529
I liked it. I would write a column and it
would run once a week. They weren't paying

00:46:55.529 --> 00:46:58.869
me to do it but that's what I did.
When I left there to do other things, for

00:46:58.869 --> 00:47:04.259
awhile I, I was teaching Effective Writing
seminars to businesspeople, which was a weird

00:47:04.259 --> 00:47:07.830
job but it was, it was good for me. It got
me around the country but I kept writing my

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:11.519
column for the Daily Local News in Westchester,
Pennsylvania, and they were paying me 22 dollars

00:47:11.519 --> 00:47:15.770
a week to do that. So I was, I was in my 30s
at this point so I clearly, I didn't think

00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:21.990
of this as a career option, just write this
little column. And then my son was born and

00:47:21.990 --> 00:47:26.921
I wrote an essay about natural childbirth
that ran in the Philadelphia Inquirer. And

00:47:26.921 --> 00:47:33.829
basically, it was a, a, I, the perfect time
for this because I'm a baby boomer and the

00:47:33.829 --> 00:47:37.140
baby boomers do everything together and they
always think they're the only ones who ever

00:47:37.140 --> 00:47:41.320
did it. And at this point we were having babies
and it never occurred to us that previous

00:47:41.320 --> 00:47:42.819
generations might have done that also.

00:47:42.819 --> 00:47:43.839
[audience laughs]

00:47:43.839 --> 00:47:48.000
It was a big deal; we had babies. And we,
of course, because we were the baby boomers,

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:52.719
we had to think of a special way to have babies.
It was called "natural childbirth" [inaudible]

00:47:52.719 --> 00:47:59.099
the idea was that instead of, like when my
mother had me the system was they gave the

00:47:59.099 --> 00:48:02.569
mother drugs, a lot of drugs, and she woke
up when you like, in the fourth grade.

00:48:02.569 --> 00:48:03.569
[audience laughs]

00:48:03.569 --> 00:48:10.810
And it was a damned good system. Everybody,
you know, but then by the time we came along

00:48:10.810 --> 00:48:15.390
we had to have a better system and our system
was you wouldn't need drugs because you practiced

00:48:15.390 --> 00:48:19.319
these relaxation techniques and breathe in
a certain way. And we went to these classes

00:48:19.319 --> 00:48:23.810
where you breathe and practice and breathe.
And it was, well, when we actually got into

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:28.359
the childbirth part where the baby coming
out part, don't try and tell a woman in that

00:48:28.359 --> 00:48:32.719
situation to just breathe a certain way. Be
glad she doesn't have a revolver if you do

00:48:32.719 --> 00:48:37.170
because basically they're just screaming for
drugs at that point. And so the-there, it

00:48:37.170 --> 00:48:40.450
was a, I remember sitting there in the room
listening to not only my wife but all these

00:48:40.450 --> 00:48:44.630
other women, you know, I have , all going,
"Aaaaaaahhhhh!!", which was not what they

00:48:44.630 --> 00:48:45.630
had, you know.

00:48:45.630 --> 00:48:51.549
So I wrote an essay about the difference between
the, the childbirth classes and the actual

00:48:51.549 --> 00:48:55.109
childbirth. And it ran in the Philadelphia
Inquirer Sunday magazine and it was the first

00:48:55.109 --> 00:49:01.569
big sale I ever had as a sense-of-humor piece.
And it did really, really well. Everybody,

00:49:01.569 --> 00:49:06.410
all these people my age, all the editors at
all the newspapers were my age, everybody's

00:49:06.410 --> 00:49:11.069
going through the same thing, they all thought
it was great. I, I, a couple days after that

00:49:11.069 --> 00:49:15.849
ran, I got a call at home from the editor
at the Chicago Tribune Sunday magazine, saying,

00:49:15.849 --> 00:49:17.610
"I read the piece on natural childbirth and
I want to reprint it in my magazine." And

00:49:17.610 --> 00:49:20.999
I thought, "Wow, that's pretty cool."

00:49:20.999 --> 00:49:24.849
Now, I had gotten paid 350 dollars, which
is the most I had ever been paid for writing

00:49:24.849 --> 00:49:29.849
something, for that piece. And he says, "How
much do you want for it?" And I think, "Well,

00:49:29.849 --> 00:49:33.609
I already got the 350", so I said, "Well,
how about 50 dollars?"

00:49:33.609 --> 00:49:34.950
[audience laughs]

00:49:34.950 --> 00:49:38.079
And there's this pause, and he goes, "How
about 500 dollars?"

00:49:38.079 --> 00:49:39.079
[audience laughs]

00:49:39.079 --> 00:49:40.549
So I said, "Ok."

00:49:40.549 --> 00:49:41.549
[audience laughs]

00:49:41.549 --> 00:49:48.579
If I'd have been smart, I'd have gone down
to 25 and, and he'd, you know.

00:49:48.579 --> 00:49:49.579
[audience laughs]

00:49:49.579 --> 00:49:52.140
He'd have probably gone to one thousand but
I took the, I took the 500. But anyway, that

00:49:52.140 --> 00:49:57.599
was my st- break in two ways. One is that
suddenly more, and after that a whole lot

00:49:57.599 --> 00:50:00.829
of other newspapers wanted to print that.
But also I discovered that, this wonderful

00:50:00.829 --> 00:50:04.589
thing that you could write something and make
more than 22 dollars for it.

00:50:04.589 --> 00:50:09.829
That, that really was how I, I, I, I think
I was just lucky in several ways. I was lucky

00:50:09.829 --> 00:50:14.670
because I was in this giant, massive humanity
all going through the same experiences and

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:21.150
I was lucky that I came along when newspapers
were strong and successful and they had magazines,

00:50:21.150 --> 00:50:24.200
which they don't have any more. Most of my
career would not be possible now, I don't

00:50:24.200 --> 00:50:27.230
think. You'd have to; you'd have to go some
other way to, to make it as a writer now.

00:50:27.230 --> 00:50:28.230
That's, I don't even remember what you're
question was.

00:50:28.230 --> 00:50:29.230
[audience laughs]

00:50:29.230 --> 00:50:31.240
I'll stop talking now before I get to--

00:50:31.240 --> 00:50:37.400
&gt;&gt;Gopi: You will probably have time for two
questions. We'll take the last one from the

00:50:37.400 --> 00:50:39.030
floor and we've trained our computers to ask
you some questions.

00:50:39.030 --> 00:50:42.140
&gt;&gt;Dave: Let me ask you, does he just always
have a microphone on when he walks around--

00:50:42.140 --> 00:50:45.150
&gt;&gt;Gopi: This is all, we're all wired. The
whole company is this way.

00:50:45.150 --> 00:50:46.150
[Dave laughs]

00:50:46.150 --> 00:50:47.529
&gt;&gt;Dave: That would be so great, yeah?

00:50:47.529 --> 00:50:49.880
&gt;&gt;Blueshirt Man: Dave, who makes you laugh?

00:50:49.880 --> 00:50:56.089
&gt;&gt;Dave: Now, a lot of, ok, I'll name a human,
Roy Blount, Jr., who is in my band and is

00:50:56.089 --> 00:51:01.809
the funniest person I know. I just say it
because I just spent a week with him, but

00:51:01.809 --> 00:51:05.959
what really, where I think the really great
humor writing is now is on television. Shows

00:51:05.959 --> 00:51:13.479
like Glee, and The Office, and Parks and Recreation,
and Community. There are all these really

00:51:13.479 --> 00:51:19.770
well-written, 30-Rock, really well-written
sitcoms; much better than they used to be.

00:51:19.770 --> 00:51:23.559
There, there was all this talk about the Golden
Age of Comedy and there was, you know M.A.S.H.

00:51:23.559 --> 00:51:27.979
and all that and All in the Family. This is
way, way more golden. Where we are right now

00:51:27.979 --> 00:51:32.960
is fabulous. I don't know who they are though.
I, I guess I know the South Park guys, who

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:36.779
they are but most of them you don't know who
they are. But the shows are really, really

00:51:36.779 --> 00:51:41.650
terrifically funny so I have to say I get
more laughs now, like I'm more reliably amused

00:51:41.650 --> 00:51:46.160
now by watching television than I am by reading
most things now. And I think that's kind of

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:49.890
what happened because people are always saying,
"Where are the humor columnists of tomorrow?"

00:51:49.890 --> 00:51:54.150
And I says, "There is no humor column for
them to write. The newspapers are disappearing."

00:51:54.150 --> 00:51:56.390
Thanks to you guys, no.

00:51:56.390 --> 00:51:57.990
[audience laughs]

00:51:57.990 --> 00:52:03.440
I don't really blame Google for that. I think
it's just, we are the, w-w-w-we're the perfect,

00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:06.739
where the newspaper industry is, is a perfect
example of why you should never allow an industry

00:52:06.739 --> 00:52:08.900
to be run by English majors.

00:52:08.900 --> 00:52:12.200
[audience laughs]

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:17.319
We could have handled it all differently,
I think. But, but that's, that's where I think

00:52:17.319 --> 00:52:21.569
they're going. That's where I think smart,
funny writers go now. And it's too bad because

00:52:21.569 --> 00:52:24.170
you don't know who they are; at least I don't
know who they are. But I think they're really

00:52:24.170 --> 00:52:27.559
good, whoever they are.

00:52:27.559 --> 00:52:29.230
Yeah? I surprised you--

00:52:29.230 --> 00:52:30.230
&gt;&gt;Gopi: We can take one more from--

00:52:30.230 --> 00:52:33.420
&gt;&gt;Dave: Yeah, I'm just going to answer the
ones that people go like, yes, no? No.

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:34.420
[audience laughs]

00:52:34.420 --> 00:52:35.420
Ok.

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:36.420
[more laughter]

00:52:36.420 --> 00:52:39.290
&gt;&gt;Gopi: We're done then. Thank you so much
for joining us. Ladies and gentlemen, Dave

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:40.290
Barry.

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:41.290
[round of applause]

00:52:41.290 --> 00:52:42.290
&gt;&gt;Dave: Thank you so much.

